(1) There are twenty-five switches located along a corridor, and a single monitoring device is to be located anywhere along the corridor so that it can receive data from the switches. There will be an expensive, dedicated communications line from the device to each of the switches it is monitoring. The distance in meters of the switches from the beginning of the corridor can be generated by running the following code:

using Statistics
Random.seed!(90555)
p = rand(1:100,25)

(1a) Determine the minimum length of the communications line that will be needed to connect all of the switches to the device and where the device should be located.

In [1]:
using Random, Statistics
Random.seed!(90555)
p = rand(1:100,25)
p = sort(p)

# First approach: Median location minimizes the sum of total distance (cf. MAD, L1)
xᵒ = median(p)
println("Minimum length of communications line (m): ", sum(abs.(xᵒ .- p)),
    "\nSwitch location (meters from beginning of corridor): ", xᵒ)

using Optim, Plots
fTD(x,p) = sum(abs.(x .- p))

xᵒ = optimize(x -> fTD(x,p),minimum(p),maximum(p)).minimizer

(1b) The device has arrived and is ready to be installed, but it turns out that it only has three ports (next time the specs will be checked before ordering). Luckily. the communications line has not yet been ordered, and so now the problem is to determine where to locate the device to minimize the length of communications line needed to reach three switches.

In [3]:
# First approach: Univariate optimization
function dist2min3pts(x,p)
    d = abs.(x .- p)
    idx = sortperm(d)
    return sum(d[idx[1:3]])
end
display(plot(x -> dist2min3pts(x,p),minimum(p),maximum(p), legend=false, xticks=p))
xᵒ = optimize(x -> dist2min3pts(x,p),minimum(p),maximum(p)).minimizer
dist2min3pts(xᵒ,p), xᵒ

(2a) Determine the total profit for all of the procedures listed in the last table of the _2-NLOpt-3 notebook except the last (Multivariate regression).

using DataFrames, XLSX, Plots, Random, Statistics, Optim
df = DataFrame(XLSX.readtable("NL_Opt-3-Data.xlsx", "52_Week_Data")...)
d,o = Int.(df.Demand),Int.(df.Orders)
display(plot(d, legend=false, xlabel="Week", ylabel="Demand", title="Original Demand"))
display(plot(d[randperm(length(d))], legend=false, 
        xlabel="Week", ylabel="Demand", title="Permuted Demand"))
display(plot(d[randperm(length(d))], legend=false, 
        xlabel="Week", ylabel="Demand", title="Permuted Demand"))

p = 5                                    # Unit price
c = 1                                    # Unit cost
fπ(q,di) = p*minimum([q, di]) - c*q      # Profit (fπ ⟹ f\pi<TAB>)  
fΠ(q,d) = sum([fπ(q,di) for di in d]);   # Total profit (fΠ ⟹ f\Pi<TAB>)

Π = sum([fπ(di,di) for di in d])
df = DataFrame(Procedure = "UB", Total_Profit = Int(round(Π)))

Π = sum([fπ(d[i-1],d[i]) for i in 2:length(d)])
push!(df,("Previous week's demand", Int(round(Π))))
Π = fΠ(mean(d),d)
push!(df,("Mean of prior demand (L2)", Int(round(Π))))
Π = fΠ(median(d),d)
push!(df,("Median of prior demand (L1)", Int(round(Π))))
Π = fΠ(optimize(q -> -fΠ(q,d), 0, 500).minimizer, d)
push!(df,("Max total profit using demand", Int(round(Π))))
        
display(plot([o d], xlabel="Week", ylabel="Units", label=["Orders" "Demand"]))
scatter(o, d, xlabel="Orders", ylabel="Demand", label="(o, d)")
@show cor(o,d)

fΠ(q,d) = sum([fπ(q[i],d[i]) for i in 1:length(d)]);    # Total profit
Π = fΠ(o,d)
push!(df,("Using just orders", Int(round(Π))))

fd̂(α,o) = α[1] .+ α[2]o
fL2(α) = sum((fd̂(α,o) .- d).^2)
α2ᵒ = optimize(α -> fL2(α), [0. 1.]).minimizer
Π = fΠ(fd̂(α2ᵒ,o),d)
push!(df,("Linear regression (L2; orders)", Int(round(Π))))
plot!(o -> fd̂(α2ᵒ,o),0,maximum(o), label="L2")

fL1(α) = sum(abs.(fd̂(α,o) .- d))
α1ᵒ = optimize(α -> fL1(α), [0. 1.]).minimizer
Π = fΠ(fd̂(α1ᵒ,o),d)
push!(df,("Linear regression (L1; orders)", Int(round(Π))))
plot!(o -> fd̂(α1ᵒ,o),0,maximum(o), label="L1", legend=true)

αΠᵒ = optimize(α -> -fΠ(fd̂(α,o),d), [0. 1.]).minimizer
Π = fΠ(fd̂(αΠᵒ,o),d)
push!(df,("Linear regression (profit; orders)", Int(round(Π))))
plot!(o -> fd̂(αΠᵒ,o),0,maximum(o), label="Π")

fd̂Q(α,o) = α[1] .+ α[2]o .+ α[3]o.^2
αΠQᵒ = optimize(α -> -fΠ(fd̂Q(α,o),d), [0. 1. 0.]).minimizer
Π = fΠ(fd̂Q(αΠQᵒ,o),d)
push!(df,("Quadratic regression (profit; orders)", Int(round(Π))))
display(plot!(o -> fd̂Q(αΠQᵒ,o),0,maximum(o), label="ΠQ", legend=:topleft))

(2c) It has been estimated that the setup cost to fulfill each week's demand is around $800, most of which are labor costs to clean, calibrate, and re-validate the equipment. It has been suggested that, because of the setup cost, it might be better not to fill any demand on weeks where demand is likely to be too low. Since this decision would need to be made at the beginning of the week, the only available data is the number of advanced orders received. It is proposed that 150 orders should be the threshold to decide each week whether to set up and then fill the demand. Determine the impact of this proposal on expected total profits. Also, a new setup is always required if any vaccine is filled for a week, even if no change has been made to the container size from the previous week.
